# Practice Exercises – HTML + CSS + JavaScript

> Exercises are grouped by difficulty. Each builds on the last.
> Every exercise has: **Goal**, **Requirements**, and **Bonus challenges**.

---

## 🟢 LEVEL 1 — Beginner (CSS + HTML)

---

### Exercise 1 — Profile Card
**Goal:** Build a styled profile card component.

**Requirements:**
- Avatar image (circle shape)
- Name, job title, short bio
- Three social icon buttons (GitHub, LinkedIn, Twitter)
- Centered on the page using Flexbox

**Concepts:** Box model, border-radius, flexbox centering, hover states

**Bonus:**
- Add a smooth hover effect that lifts the card (`transform: translateY`)
- Make it responsive — full width on mobile

---

### Exercise 2 — Responsive Navigation Bar
**Goal:** Build a top navigation bar.

**Requirements:**
- Logo on the left, nav links on the right
- Active link has a different color + underline
- Links have hover effects

**Concepts:** Flexbox, `justify-content: space-between`, pseudo-classes

**Bonus:**
- On mobile (< 768px), stack links vertically
- Add a sticky navbar that stays at top on scroll

---

### Exercise 3 — CSS Grid Photo Gallery
**Goal:** Create a photo grid gallery.

**Requirements:**
- At least 6 images in a grid
- 3 columns on desktop, 2 on tablet, 1 on mobile
- Uniform card size, images fit without distortion (`object-fit: cover`)

**Concepts:** CSS Grid, `auto-fit`, `minmax`, `object-fit`, media queries

**Bonus:**
- Make one featured image span 2 columns
- Add a hover overlay with the image title

---

### Exercise 4 — Pricing Table
**Goal:** Build a 3-column pricing table (Basic / Pro / Enterprise).

**Requirements:**
- Each card: plan name, price, list of features, CTA button
- Middle card ("Pro") is highlighted differently (different border/background)
- Fully responsive

**Concepts:** Flexbox or Grid, CSS variables for colors, `transform: scale` on featured card

**Bonus:**
- Animate the highlighted card with a pulsing box-shadow
- Add a toggle switch between Monthly / Annual pricing

---

## 🟡 LEVEL 2 — Intermediate (JS + DOM)

---

### Exercise 5 — Counter App
**Goal:** Build an interactive counter.

**Requirements:**
- Display a number starting at 0
- Three buttons: Increment, Decrement, Reset
- Number turns red when negative, green when positive

**Concepts:** DOM manipulation, `classList`, event listeners, conditional styling

**Bonus:**
- Add a step input — user sets how much to increment/decrement
- Save the count to `localStorage` so it persists on refresh

---

### Exercise 6 — To-Do List App
**Goal:** Build a fully functional to-do list.

**Requirements:**
- Input field + Add button to create tasks
- Each task has a ✅ Complete toggle and 🗑 Delete button
- Completed tasks have strikethrough style
- Show total count of remaining tasks

**Concepts:** DOM creation, event delegation, classList, array state

**Bonus:**
- Filter buttons: All / Active / Completed
- Save tasks to `localStorage` — persist on refresh
- Allow editing a task by double-clicking it

---

### Exercise 7 — Form Validation
**Goal:** Build a registration form with full client-side validation.

**Fields:** Name, Email, Password, Confirm Password, Age

**Requirements:**
- Validate on submit (not just on blur)
- Show inline error messages below each invalid field
- Show red border on invalid fields, green on valid
- Don't submit unless all fields pass

**Validation rules:**
- Name: required, min 3 characters
- Email: required, valid format
- Password: min 8 characters, must contain a number
- Confirm Password: must match password
- Age: required, must be 18–100

**Concepts:** Form events, `preventDefault`, regex, DOM manipulation

**Bonus:**
- Live validation as user types (on `input` event)
- Show a password strength meter (Weak / Medium / Strong)

---

### Exercise 8 — Live Search / Filter
**Goal:** Build a product list with live search filtering.

**Requirements:**
- Hardcode an array of 10+ products (name, category, price)
- Render all products as cards on page load
- Search input filters products by name in real time
- Show "No results found" when nothing matches

**Concepts:** Array `filter`, DOM re-rendering, event listeners on input

**Bonus:**
- Add category dropdown filter (combine with search)
- Debounce the search input (300ms)
- Sort by price (Low → High / High → Low)

---

### Exercise 9 — Quiz App
**Goal:** Build a multi-question quiz.

**Requirements:**
- Array of 5 questions with 4 options each
- Show one question at a time
- Highlight correct (green) and wrong (red) answers on selection
- Track and display score at the end
- Restart button to retake

**Concepts:** Arrays of objects, DOM rendering, conditional logic, state management

**Bonus:**
- Add a countdown timer per question (15 seconds)
- Show which questions were answered wrong at the end
- Animate the progress bar between questions

---

## 🔴 LEVEL 3 — Advanced (Async + Fetch + Full DOM)

---

### Exercise 10 — Weather App
**Goal:** Fetch and display real weather data.

**API:** `https://wttr.in/{city}?format=j1` (free, no key needed)

**Requirements:**
- Input for city name + Search button
- Display: city name, temperature, weather condition, humidity
- Show loading spinner while fetching
- Show error message if city not found

**Concepts:** Fetch API, async/await, try/catch, DOM manipulation, loading states

**Bonus:**
- Show 3-day forecast
- Save last searched city in `localStorage`
- Add debounce to auto-search as user types

---

### Exercise 11 — GitHub User Search
**Goal:** Search GitHub users and display their profiles.

**API:** `https://api.github.com/users/{username}` (free)

**Requirements:**
- Search input for GitHub username
- Display: avatar, name, bio, public repos count, followers, following
- Clickable link to their GitHub profile
- Handle user not found (404)

**Concepts:** Fetch, async/await, error handling by status code, conditional rendering

**Bonus:**
- Also fetch and display their latest 5 repos
- Add skeleton loading cards while fetching

---

### Exercise 12 — Expense Tracker
**Goal:** A complete expense tracking mini-app.

**Requirements:**
- Add expense: description, amount, category (Food/Transport/Shopping/Other)
- Display all expenses in a list with delete button
- Show total balance at top
- Separate totals by category
- Persist data in `localStorage`

**Concepts:** localStorage, array methods, DOM rendering, event delegation, `reduce`

**Bonus:**
- Edit existing expenses
- Export as CSV (using Blob and anchor download)
- Chart showing spending by category (CSS bar chart, no library)

